text:
Don't miss out on any of our exclusive football, basketball and recruiting coverage. Click here to get your 30-day free trial!
Seneca Milledge is a standout on the track and football field at Fort Myers (Fla.) Dunbar. Former All-Big Ten selection Aaron Henry was announced as NC State's new safeties coach Jan. 19. His presence is already paying dividends, evidenced by the commitment of 2019 athlete Seneca Milledge of Fort Myers (Fla.) Dunbar. He announced his commitment Tuesday, and The Wolfpacker has since confirmed it.
Henry is a native of Immokalee, Fla., and then he played at Wisconsin under current NCSU head coach Dave Doeren. After being announced as the newest Pack assistant, he penned a letter to his safeties, explaining his background.
Personal #STATEMENT : A letter to the safeties from @AaronHenry7 https://t.co/prQ0PCOtWj

Six days later, Milledge is the newest member of the Pack.
He reportedly runs a 4.41-second 40-yard dash and also had offers from Miami, Maryland and others. According to News-Press.com , the sophomore defended an area-high 14 passes, made 71 tackles, forced a fumble and snared an interception this past season. He's also a standout the track, winning district and region titles (10.53 seconds) in the 100-meter dash as a freshman before an injury hampered his performance at the state championship.
Last March he set new national records for the 55 and 200 indoor sprints at the USATF Hershey‚Äôs National Youth Indoor Track and Field Championships in Staten Island, New York. He ran the 55 in 6.34 seconds and the 200 in 21.72 seconds. He is also ranked No. 1 by Dyestat.com in the outdoor 100-meter sprint for his grade.
